\section{How To Use This Report}
\label{sec:how-to-use-this-report}
Welcome to your \gls{CyHy} report. This document aims to be a comprehensive weekly snapshot of known \glspl{vulnerability} detected on Internet-facing \glspl{host} for \gls{AGENCY}.

You may wonder what you're supposed to do with all this information. While it's not our intent to prescribe to you a particular process for remediating vulnerabilities, we hope you'll use this report to strengthen your security posture. Here's a basic flow:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Review the \hyperref[sec:report-card]{Cyber Hygiene Report Card} for a high-level overview. This section gives a quick comparison of the problems we find week to week. If this is your first report, you should note that the Report Card will initially lack historical data to make comparisons against, though that data will exist in your next report.
<<#owner_is_federal_executive>>
\item Review the \hyperref[sec:ed1901]{Emergency Directive 19-01 ---
  New Certificates Summary} for current certificate information. This
  section gives a quick look at the currently expired, soon to expire,
  and newly added certificates for known hostnames owned by or managed
  on behalf of your organization.
<</owner_is_federal_executive>>
\item See \autoref{app:detected-vulnerabilities}: \nameref{app:detected-vulnerabilities} for a list of unique vulnerabilities across all the systems we detect problems with. \autoref{app:detailed-findings}: \nameref{app:detailed-findings} provides more information about each vulnerability and all the hosts that we detect are susceptible to a given vulnerability. You should focus on those vulnerabilities rated with the greatest \gls{severity}, as well as those that impact your high-value assets, but don't ignore the medium or low vulnerabilities. Recognize that a vulnerability's rating tends to get worse with time.
\item If this report is not your first, review \autoref{app:vuln-changes-since-last-report}: \nameref{app:vuln-changes-since-last-report} for a breakdown of all the changes we detected in your scope in the last week.
\item If you've patched a vulnerability since your last report, verify it's listed here. If it's not present, there may still be an issue. It may also be possible that the issue was fixed after our latest scan, which was on \usvardate\formatdate<<&calc.end_date_tex>>.
\item For additional analysis, see \autoref{app:attachments}: \nameref{app:attachments}, which provides \gls{CSV} files for all findings, \glspl{service}, hosts, and the scope that we scan.
\item Review \autoref{app:false-positive-findings}: \nameref{app:false-positive-findings} to track any upcoming expiration dates for false positive designations. For any new false positives, please complete and return to \gls{NCATS} the False Positive Assertion Form found in \autoref{app:attachments}: \nameref{app:attachments}.
\end{enumerate}

You should be aware that Cyber Hygiene does not scan your entire scope (all of the addresses your organization has sent us) every week, but does attempt to scan every \gls{host} each week. For an explanation of how \gls{CyHy} works, see the \nameref{sec:methodology} section.

As you review the report, you may have additional questions. Check out the answers we provide in the \nameref{app:FAQ} section. If you have any additional questions, email us at  \href{mailto:ncats@hq.dhs.gov}{ncats@hq.dhs.gov}.

