\section{Methodology}
\label{sec:methodology}
\subsection{Background}
The \gls{NCATS} team conducted a Cyber Hygiene assessment of \gls{AGENCY}'s Internet-facing networks and \glspl{host} from \usvardate\formatdate<<&calc.start_date_tex>> at \formattime<<&calc.start_time_tex>> UTC through \usvardate\formatdate<<&calc.end_date_tex>> at \formattime<<&calc.end_time_tex>> UTC. This report provides result summaries and detailed findings of the \gls{CyHy} assessment activity for \gls{AGENCY}<<#display_owner>> and its associated sub-organizations<</display_owner>>. All scan results are included in \autoref{app:attachments}: \nameref{app:attachments} as \gls{CSV} files.

Cyber Hygiene is intended to improve your security posture by proactively identifying and reporting on \glspl{vulnerability} and configuration issues present on Internet-facing systems before those vulnerabilities can be exploited.

Cyber Hygiene is a service of \gls{NCATS}, organized under the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (\gls{CISA}).

\gls{CISA} began Cyber Hygiene in January 2012 to assess, on a recurring basis, the ``health" of unclassified federal civilian networks accessible via the Internet. Since then, the program has grown to provide a persistent scanning service to federal, state, local, tribal, and territorial governments and private sector organizations.

Upon submission of an Acceptance Letter, \gls{AGENCY} provided \gls{NCATS} with their public network address information. \gls{AGENCY} and \gls{NCATS} agreed on any time restrictions which would be imposed on the scanning activity.

\subsection{Process}
\label{subsec:methodology-process}
All Cyber Hygiene scanning activity originates from a dynamic set of \gls{AWS} \gls{IP} addresses in the US East and US West regions. The live list of active addresses can be found at \href{https://rules.ncats.cyber.dhs.gov}{https://rules.ncats.cyber.dhs.gov}. The addresses in that list will change based on overall \gls{CyHy} scan demand.

\gls{CyHy} uses a combination of scanning services for testing:
\begin{itemize}
\item Network Mapping
\item Vulnerability Scanning
\end{itemize}

\textbf{\underline{Network Mapping}}

Using Nmap [\href{https://nmap.org}{https://nmap.org}], we attempt to determine what \glspl{host} are available, identify what \glspl{service} (application name and version) those hosts are offering, and what \gls{OS} versions they are running. We first scan the most commonly detected 1,000 \gls{TCP} ports of the addresses you've submitted to us to get a quick understanding of the active/dark landscape. An address that has a least one port open/listening service is considered a \textit{host} and is then fully port-scanned (\gls{TCP}) and included in the vulnerability scan.  For the purposes of this report, \textit{tcpwrapped} ports are not considered to be open; for more information on tcpwrapped ports, refer to the \nameref{app:FAQ} section.

If no services are detected in the most common 1,000 ports on a given \gls{IP} address, that address is considered ``dark" in \gls{CyHy} and will be re-scanned after at least 90 days to check for change. Addresses marked dark are not included in the host count of the weekly report. Understand that \gls{CyHy} is not attempting to make a judgment call about why an address is unresponsive. If there's not a port open, it's not a \textit{host} in the language of \gls{CyHy}.

\newpage
\textbf{\underline{Vulnerability Scanning}}

Using Nessus, a commercial vulnerability scanner, each host is evaluated against a library of vulnerabilities that an Internet-based actor could exploit. Vulnerabilities are reported with a severity of critical, high, medium, or low to facilitate prioritization of remediation efforts. We enable all \href{https://www.tenable.com/plugins/}{Nessus Plugins} [\href{https://www.tenable.com/plugins/}{https://www.tenable.com/plugins/}] except those in the ``Denial of Service" family.

\textbf{\underline{Scanning Frequency}}

Scanning occurs continuously between each weekly report. All \glspl{host} are scanned for \glspl{vulnerability} at least once every two weeks; hosts with vulnerabilities are scanned more frequently.

Cyber Hygiene's scan prioritization is as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item Addresses with no running \glspl{service} detected (dark space) are rescanned after at least 90 days.
\item Hosts with no vulnerabilities detected are rescanned every 7 days.
\item Hosts with low-severity vulnerabilities are rescanned every 6 days.
\item Hosts with medium-severity vulnerabilities are rescanned every 4 days.
\item Hosts with high-severity vulnerabilities are rescanned every 24 hours.
\item Hosts with critical-severity vulnerabilities are rescanned every 12 hours.
\end{itemize}

You should understand that a single host may have multiple vulnerabilities of varying \gls{severity}, which impacts the frequency that the host is scanned.

To be clear, it is not the case that we scan your entire address scope for vulnerabilities each week (unless each address you've provided to us has a responsive host). It is the case, though, that each host will get vulnerability scanned at least once per week.

\textbf{\underline{Recurring Vulnerabilities}}

After you've remediated a vulnerability (and it remains resolved for a period of 90 days), the host's scan priority will drop. This approach allows the \gls{NCATS} team to focus on the areas of importance and give more attention to the hosts that need it.

Vulnerabilities are assigned an age in order to track timeliness of remediation. \Gls{vulnerability age} is determined by when it was first detected on a host, not from when it first appeared on a report. As scanning occurs continuously between weekly reports, it is possible to have ``new" vulnerabilities appear on a report that are already days old. It is also possible for a vulnerability to fluctuate between being detected and not detected during mid-week scans and then at a future time appear in a report as many days old.  If a mitigated vulnerability is re-detected less than 90 days after the date of non-detection, it will be considered to be the same vulnerability with the same ``\gls{initial detection} date" as previously recorded. If it is re-detected more than 90 days after the date of non-detection, it will be treated as a new vulnerability with a new ``initial detection date".

\newpage
\textbf{\underline{Vulnerability Scoring}}

The Nessus vulnerability scanner references the \gls{NVD} [\href{https://nvd.nist.gov/}{https://nvd.nist.gov/}] for its vulnerability information. The \gls{NVD} provides \gls{CVSS} scores for many known vulnerabilities. In particular, \gls{NVD} supports the \gls{CVSS} version standard for all \gls{CVE} vulnerabilities.

The \gls{CVSS} is a free and open industry standard for assessing the severity of computer system security vulnerabilities. \gls{CVSS} attempts to assign severity scores to vulnerabilities, allowing responders to prioritize responses and resources according to threat. The \gls{NVD} uses severity rankings of ``Low," ``Medium," and ``High" in addition to the numeric \gls{CVSS} scores, but these qualitative rankings are simply mapped from the numeric \gls{CVSS} base scores:
\begin{itemize}
\item Vulnerabilities are labeled ``Low" severity if they have a \gls{CVSS} base score of 0.0-3.9.
\item Vulnerabilities will be labeled ``Medium" severity if they have a base \gls{CVSS} score of 4.0-6.9.
\item Vulnerabilities will be labeled ``High" severity if they have a \gls{CVSS} base score of 7.0-10.0.
\end{itemize}
Nessus has a ``critical" rating which it uses for \gls{CVSS} 10 vulnerabilities. Where the \gls{NVD} has not provided a \gls{CVE} severity rating, the Nessus scanner relies on its own rankings.

\textbf{\underline{What's In The Report?}}

Though Cyber Hygiene initiates multiple scans between reports, \textit{only the latest scan data for each host is used to determine current vulnerability}. This is the data that appears in the main body of the report and in \autoref{app:detected-vulnerabilities}: \nameref{app:detected-vulnerabilities}, \autoref{app:new-vulnerabilities}: \nameref{app:new-vulnerabilities} and \autoref{app:redetected-vulnerabilities}: \nameref{app:redetected-vulnerabilities}.

If a vulnerability was detected since that last report (e.g., it wasn't in the previous report's findings, though \gls{CyHy} saw it mid-week) but it was not in the latest scan, we include it in \autoref{app:recently-detected-vulnerabilities}: \nameref{app:recently-detected-vulnerabilities}.

If a vulnerability that was previously reported to you is no longer detected by the latest scan, the vulnerability and host will be listed in \autoref{app:mitigated-vulnerabilities}: \nameref{app:mitigated-vulnerabilities}.

We encourage you to validate the status of vulnerabilities in both \autoref{app:mitigated-vulnerabilities}: \nameref{app:mitigated-vulnerabilities} and \autoref{app:recently-detected-vulnerabilities}: \nameref{app:recently-detected-vulnerabilities} against your change control register. This will help to ensure that the vulnerability we detected has actually been remediated and is not simply unresponsive to our scans.

